Lee 223 Factory Crimp Die crimps the bullet in place more firmly than any other tool. Tests demonstrate that even bullets which have no crimp groove will shoot more accurately. A firm crimp improves accuracy because pressure must build to a higher level before the bullet begins to move. This higher start pressure insures a more uniform pressure curve and less velocity variation.

The Lee Precision Factory Crimp Die is designed to give reloaders the perfect crimp on each round of reloaded ammunition. The Factory Crimp Die crimps the bullet more firmly in place than any other die with more uniform pressure. The Factory Crimp Die features a collet that squeezes the case mouth into the crimping groove for a firm hold. It is nearly impossible to buckle the case when crimping when compared to a regular roll crimp die. Lee's testing has shown that using a Factory Crimp Die provides a more uniform pressure curve, increasing the accuracy of any bullet. Shellholder sold separately.

title: For Sale:  Burris 3-9X-40 Fullfield II Ballistic Plex Riflescope AND 10X-32mm Landmark Binocular
postcontent:
BRAND NEW in factory sealed package. Scope by itself retails for $200, so you're basically getting the binoculars for free (which retail for $115). Willing to ship for $15.00 extra.

Burris 3-9x40mm Fullfield II Rifle Scope w/ Burris 10x32mm Landmark Binoculars gives you a full spot-and-shoot package! This value package from Burris includes the Burris 3x-9x 40mm Fullfield-II Riflescope and the Burris Landmark 10x32mm Binoculars.

The Burris Fullfield II Rifle Scope has a one-piece main tube and eyepiece, Burris envied steel-on-steel adjustment system, and HiLume multi-coatings on every single air to glass lens surface. The Burris FullField-II Scope is even more forgiving for eye position, is a little shorter, and a good bit lighter. The magnification ring and eyepiece have been made into one solid unit requiring only two seals rather than three. To change magnification, simply turn the entire eyepiece. Burris Fullfield 2 Scope eliminated most of the potential leak paths in the eyepiece/power ring area and sealed the remainder with special quad seals instead of O-rings. The adjustment system has been moved to improve mounting options and the European-style adjustable eyepiece requires no locking mechanism. The Ballistic Plex reticle has a lower vertical crosshair with small ballistic lines that automatically compensate for bullet drop from 100 to 500 yards for many common cartridges. The Burris Fullfield-2 Riflescope is lighter, better sealed, and has a relocated adjustment system compared to the original Burris Fullfield.

The Burris Landmark Binoculars combine light weight, fully coated lenses and water resistant, fogproof construction. These Burris Binoculars also include a tough rubber armor coating and twist-up eyecups. Top all this off with a neck strap, carrying case, a full year warranty and a very affordable price and you have yourself a synonym for optical value.

Features of Burris 3-9x40mm Fullfield II Rifle Scope:

Waterproof: All Burris optics are proven to be absolutely waterproof. Each scope is submerged in water with a temperature of 50° C. The extremely hot water transfers its heat to the scope and the internal nitrogen expends 100% testing assures quality. Each scope is filled and purged at least 24 times with high quality, laboratory grade dry nitrogen. Each nitrogen cycle absorbs airborne and residual surface moisture that is evacuated from the scope. Burris uses specially made quad seals to provide double insurance against leakage.
Fog proof: The nitrogen contained in the scope is of high quality (ultra dry, laboratory grade nitrogen), ultra pure and ultra clean. To be sure that all airborne moisture and surfaces moisture within a scope is evacuated, testing consists of 24 cycles of pressurizing the scope and then subjecting it to a vacuum. The tests are both cost & time intensive.
Shock proof: Burris scopes are subjected to extreme recoil tests. An impact machine is used to measure and duplicate the recoil pulse acceleration and duration. This machine has been calibrated and verified by an independent laboratory to replicate the wave frequencies and shock impulses that a scope is subjected to.
Ballistic Plex reticle - with a basic crosshair reticle, calculating hold-over is a mix of art, science and just plain luck, which is why Burris developed the Ballistic Plex reticle. The key is the copyrighted lower vertical crosshair. With most common hunting cartridges, a shooter can use the reticle to compensate for bullet drop and aim dead-on at targets from 100 to 500 yards out. The need for hold-over guesstimation is eliminated. Using it is simple. Start by sighting-in your rifle at 100 or 200 yards at your scope's highest magnification. Then, once you determine the distance to your target, select the appropriate ballistic line. Add slight hold-over or hold-under for in-between yardages and take the shot.

title: For Sale:  FN 308 Patrol Bolt Rifle -RARE-
location: South of Farmville, Greenville, North Carolina
postcontent:
FN Herstal Patrol Bolt Rifle (PBR) in 308 caliber, with the 22" medium bull barrel.
In case you're not familiar, this rifle is based on the Pre-64 Winchester model 70 action, which is generally held by real shooters to be one of the finest rifle bolt actions ever made. It's rock-solid and designed to outlast me, you, and your kids.

Hogue fully overmolded stock with a solid aluminum bedding block/pillar system, free floating the barrel.

The scope is a cheap NCStar, but it's VERY high powered (10-40x!) and worked well the day I tried it out.

It includes a Harris-type bipod (not sure of brand, may be a Harris, not sure) and a really nice padded tactical (shock) sling.

The metal has been Duracoated in Flat Dark Earth (FDE) inside and out to protect from the elements, should you decide you need to shoot in foul weather.

This is an extremely rare rifle. There is exactly 1 like it for sale on gunbroker, and none that I can find on Armslist, if that tells you anything.

I've only had it to the range once (got it in trade a while back), but it shot just over 1 MOA with cheap steel case FMJ ammo at 200 yards in a nasty gusting crosswind. All the reviews and range reports I've found say that it's easily sub-MOA with decent ammo. I have no reason to doubt it.

The previous owner told me he had some bolt work done to it, so it's supposed to be slicker than stock. I don't have anything to compare it to, but the action is very smooth.

The trigger is adjustable. I'm not sure how it's set at the moment, but my "finger scale" says it feels like around 3.5 lbs with very little travel, so I'm happy.

I'm not really looking to trade, since that would defeat the purpose of "getting rid of a few guns", but you're welcome to offer if you have something you think I might like.

I am only selling because it is my second AR and I would like to go into the .308 AR/AR10 platform, so something has to go!  

If you had not heard, Windham Weaponry is basically a new & improved Bushmaster, the company was founded by Bushmaster's original owner, and employs many of the original Bushmaster employees pre-Freedom Group buyout.  A cool feature of Windham rifles are that it includes a TRANSFERABLE lifetime warranty, so any buyer will benefit form this.  MSRP on this rifle is $1680, and I haven't seen them under $1600 right now.  It's a VERY well made rifle with some high quality components - magpul grip, AFG, and stock, Diamondhead BUIS (the set costs almost $300 alone), Diamondhead Rail, Vortex flash hider.  Also includes 30 round magazine, sling, printed materials, and hard case.  5.56 chamber so you are good to go with .223 AND 5.56 ammunition.

title: For Sale:  2 WW2 Sniper Rifles, WW1 Mosin plus 1200 rounds of ammo
postcontent:
For sale are my WW2 sniper rifles and a scarce WW1 1916 dated steoyeskey arsenal built mosin M91 that is in good condition For being close to 100 years old with a good bore and nice wood. The rifle shoots great and I believe it to either be a ww1 or ww2 bringback since it exhibits no importation markings. The second rifle is an original 1943 dated nagant PU sniper which is also a bring back as it has no importation markings. The only drawback I can see is the previous owner stated the scope had a very worn finish so he reblued the scope. Not really a big deal as the finish on the gun is still original but it was worth mentioning for full disclosure. Rifle is very accurate and shoots well. Very hard to find bring back originals as most are reproductions. Lastly I have a Mauser 24/47 sniper that I
Purchased about 10 years ago that was dubbed a Balkan war sniper They were sold around 2002-2003 as imported. Some came with bases and even scopes but mine was purchased as just the gun with the holes already drilled into the reciever as was done by the army who fielded it as a sniper. Once I received the gun I sent it off to a
Mauser guru who builds guns back to orginal WW2 sniper spec and he completely redid the rifle from top to bottom at the cost of $1200. He basically did about everything you can do to a rifle to make it more accurate from bedding the stock, to action job, to trigger job. He also tru cut the chamber for accuracy as well as trimming any wood that made contact with the barrel and trimmed the barrel bands so they no longer touched the barrel as well. He then topped it off with a vintage weaver scope that looks identical to the ww2 German scopes and added quick release rings for easy scope removal. The results are the rifle shoots half inch 100 yard groups all day long with off the shelf hunting ammo. This rifle is not only a nice example of a WW2 sniper it is also an amazingly accurate shooter that will out shoot most modern snipers. I have tons of money invested into this gun and it shows with not only performance but looks as well. I will also include an additional 3 post reticle scope. I also have 880 rounds of 7.62x54 ammo and 350 rounds of yugo surplus ammo I will include. Looking to sell everything as one lot for $2500 which is a bargain as I have close to $2000 invested in the Mauser alone. Will consider partial trades for original WW1 era 1911s and possibly WW2 1911 A1s. E-mail, call, or text REDACTED.

Technical Information:

Its 5.56x45mm NATO Chamber is fully compatible and safe for use with both surplus mil-spec and commercial ammunition, while its 1 in 7" Rifling Twist Rate is ideal for use with medium to heavy weight projectiles of up to about 77 grains. title: For Sale:  Promount #8711 scope rail for Remington 870, 1100, 1187 12 gauge guns
location: White Bear Lake area, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
Here's an older but never used Promont scope rail for Remington 12 gauge shotguns.
According to my research, these are no longer made but are excellent quality, VERY STURDY and lightweight mounts. Made in Waukesha Wisconsin, this is a one-piece extruded alloy mount wiht a standard Weaver rail on the top and two screws and washers to attach it to the left side of your receiver. This one has been screwed onto a gun once but no scope rings have ever been attached so it is basically new.

Simply remove the small and large trigger pins, install the mount and insert the screws with nylon washers from the right side, then snug them up and install your optics choice on the rail (no rings included but any ring that will fit a Weaver rail will work).
You can quickly mount your scope, red-dot or holographic sight on your shotgun for either hunting turkey or combat competition (three gun).
This should all the 12 gauge Remingtons with two dissimilar pins holding the trigger in. It will NOT fit 20 gauge models as it is, BUT you could easily drill another hole to match your 20 gauge receiver, then it should work just fine.

This has an old price tag on the box of 40 bucks, and these were never cheap. One recently sold on Ebay for $29.95 and shipping:

http://www.ebay.com/itm/Promount-Scope-Mount-Model-8711-for-Remington-870-1100-12-ga-USA-/REDACTED89?nma=true&si=xOxAMd%252B%252BTM74jBr1pJAhVfQMvIM%253D&orig_cvip=true&rt=nc&_trksid=p2047675.l2557

title: For Sale:  Beeman Sportsman .22 Air Rifle (Upgraded Spring/Piston)
postcontent:
TL;DR: Awesome air rifle for $150.

I have for sale my Beeman Sportsman .22 caliber air rifle.
(Not the craptastic dual-barrel Wallyworld special that has brought shame to the Beeman name.)

I'm selling this because I moved into a house in the suburbs of Knoxville.
My yard is too small to for any shot to be a challenge, and houses surround me in every direction.
I'm looking to sell this air rifle to someone that will come to love it as much as I do.

This rifle was a project to turn a fairly low cost air rifle($200) into something that shot like a top dollar air rifle such as the $700 Beeman R1 Supermagnum.
My father and I started by going through quite a few boxes to find the air rifle with the best tolerances out of the box, paying special attention to the rifling as that was pertty much the only part we did not intend to replace and then sent it off to recieve a Maccari spring, guide, and seal kit.
(This kit is considered one of the best, if not THE best.)
As a result, the velocity was increased and the velocity is amazingly consistant between shots. It also reduces vibration and spring twist, which reduces the felt recoil and improves accuracy greatly.
We considered a new trigger, but the RS2 trigger is a highly adjustable two-stage trigger that ended up feeling well...awesome.
(Imagine a glass rod breaking, you have to feel it to believe it.)
I left on the iron sights, mostly for redundance...it will come with the original 4x32 scope that isn't all that bad.
(I've been using a Bugbuster, but I'm keeping that.)

This air rifle has been chronoed at 850 FPS with LEAD pellets, not the non-lead ultra-light alloy pellets (that don't group worth a rats ass) that most airguns are rated with.
It's capable of some amazing groups at 50 yards, I can keep most of my shots on a quarter...and I sometimes shoot at 150 yards at 5x5 inch steel plates just for giggles.
(keep in mind this is a springer and requires a special artillery hold)

I love this air rifle, I'll be sad to see it go.
Only make an offer if you'll take care of it and use it.
With proper maintainance, this thing will be able to be passed to your kids.

So basically, $200 for rifle + $99 for spring/piston kit + 50 for seals and lubes = $350.
...for a rifle that shoots as well or better than a $700 German made air rifle

To answer some questions I'm sure I'll get...
It was purchased by my father in 1996, back when they were running out of Huntington Beach, CA and the Beeman name still meant something.
(Springs and seals have all been replaced as needed.)
Yes, it was "Made In China".
(However, it is not an inferior product. This rifle is a QUALITY product with great tolerances.)
I've never put locktite on any of the threads, as with proper maintainance it's not required due to it not vibrating heavily after every shot.
(Just make sure they're tight before a shooting session, 1/4 turn of the two screws at the front of the forearm can open your groups up 1/2 inch at 50yds.)

Thanks for looking.

postcontent:
Looking a real "FIREPOWER". Then here it is. Comes with 4 extra 20 round magazines, Low profile claw type scope mount and 240 rounds of Lake City ammo. 

Weapon Specifications:

Caliber:                .308 or 7.62 NATO
Action:                Delayed Blowback Roller-Lock System
Overall length:      23 ½ “
Weight:               7.55 lb
Barrel:                 8 1/8” Match Grade, Bull barrel, Treaded and comes with HK Flash 
                          hider.
Magazine:            20rd
Stock:                 machined butt cap (optional retractable stock)
Trigger:               H&K Navy type polymer trigger group
Hand Guard:         Tactical handguard machined from military spec. hard anodized 
                          aluminum rail ready.

                                   HISTORY OF ORIGINATION

PTR-91, is a family of modern, American-manufactured civilian semi automatic rifles. The design is a variation of the Heckler and Koch G3/HK91 rifles. These rifles are produced by PTR Industries, Inc. of Bristol, Connecticut. The abbreviation PTR stands for "Precision Target Rifle".

The assault weapons ban of 1994 (which expired in 2004) prohibited certain cosmetic features of the HK91, meaning that it could no longer be manufactured and sold to the US civilian market in its original configuration. Furthermore, the German-made HK91 was specifically prohibited from importation under the 1989 Import Ban. Subsequently Heckler and Koch ceased manufacture of the semi-automatic HK91, and since then civilian versions of the G3 have increased in collector value. The PTR-91 was developed to fill the void, as the two rifles are almost identical.

JLD Enterprises ("JLD") began manufacturing ban compliant PTR-91 rifles in 2002, after purchasing prints and tooling from Fabrica Militar of Portugal - an HK licensed factory. The ban compliant models did not have a threaded barrel, bayonet lugs, adjustable stocks, or "high capacity" magazines. Very early models, being produced directly from the purchased prints were nearly identical to the HK91 with the exception of modifications for compliance with the assault weapons ban. After the ban's expiration in 2004, JLD began offering a wider range of PTR-91 models, many of which featured more of the original military features. JLD also began investing in research and development, and debuted many new improvements and modifications to the original HK91 design. Initially, JLD produced rifles relied heavily on imported military surplus components for G3/HK91 rifles. In fact, most parts between the HK-91 and the PTR-91 are interchangeable.
